===Glyph origin===
{{Han etyl}}
Unclear. Possibly taken from an oracle-bone form of {{och-l|智|tr=*treh}}, composed of {{zh-l|*子}}, {{zh-l|*止}} and {{zh-l|*冊}}.<ref>陳劍：《古文字基礎形體研究》，南京大學文學院暑期班課程，2022年。</ref><ref>詹鄞鑫：《釋甲骨文“知”字——兼説商代的舊禮與新禮》，《華夏考：詹鄞鑫文字訓詁論集》，北京：中華書局，2006年，第369～375頁。</ref><ref>李艾希：《考釋商周古文所見“智”字構形之三個問題》，《中國文字》2022年冬季號（總第8期）</ref>

===Etymology===
“This [an independent pronoun] > this, it [object recapitulation], be right, correct, so > to be, indeed”. The modern copulative sense only emerged by the Eastern Han dynasty ({{zh-ref|Dobson, 1964}}; {{zh-ref|Norman, 1988}}; {{zh-ref|Zürcher, 2013}}), and gradually replaced the archaic {{och-l|唯|to be|id=1}} and the classical copulative construction with {{och-l|也}}. 

This was due to the lack of a left-branching copula as archaic 唯 shifted into a contrasting and restricting particle, as well as its frequent use in presentational copulative constructions, often in the form of "A, 是 B 也" ("A, this is B"), which led to it being gradually reinterpreted as the copula instead of 也. Also note the semantic opposition with literary negative copula {{och-l|非}} as in "right" and "wrong", which emerged by the Warring States period from the frequent collocation of the expression "是 X 也, 非 Y 也" (This is X, not Y) ({{zh-ref|Pulleyblank, 1995}}) . 

To understand this development, compare {{och-l|之|him, it, this > possessive}}, {{och-l|其|he, his, its > dialectal possessive|id=1}}. Compare French {{m|fr|c'est}} which in colloquial speech often replaces copula {{m|fr|est}}.

From {{inh|zh|sit-pro|*m-daj ~ m-di||that; this}}. In Chinese, cognate with {{och-l|寔|this (subject contrastive) }}, {{och-l|實|this (subject contrastive) }}, {{och-l|之|this; him; her; it (oblique) }}, {{och-l|諟|to examine, to consider}}. In Tibeto-Burman, cognate with {{cog|bo|དེ||that}}, {{cog|kac|dai}}, {{m|kac|ndai||this}}, and {{cog|my|ဒီ||this}}.

